and .map() only works on arrays

.map() works only on arrays, but you must understand why and how it is different from a normal loop.

I will explain it as simply as possible.

âœ… 1. What is .map()?

.map() is a special array method.

It is used to:

âœ” loop over each item in an array
âœ” return a new array
âœ” perfect for displaying lists in React

Example:

const names = ["Siti", "Eliyas", "Abdulaziz"];

const result = names.map(n => "Hello " + n);
// ["Hello Siti", "Hello Eliyas", "Hello Abdulaziz"]

ðŸ¤” 2. What is a loop (for, while)?

A normal loop (like for) just repeats code.

Example:

for (let i = 0; i < names.length; i++) {
  console.log(names[i]);
}


âž¡ It does NOT automatically return a new array.
âž¡ It just runs code many times.

ðŸ”¥ 3. The BIG difference
Feature	.map()	Loop (for, while)
Returns a new array	âœ… Yes	âŒ No
Best for React list rendering	âœ… Yes	âŒ Not ideal
Cleaner, shorter	âœ… Yes	âŒ Longer
Works only on arrays	âœ… Yes	âŒ Works everywhere
ðŸ’¡ 4. Why React loves .map()

In React, you return JSX:

const items = ["a", "b", "c"];

return (
  <ul>
    {items.map((item) => (
      <li>{item}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>
);


You CANNOT write:

for (...) {
  return <li>...</li>   âŒ Not allowed
}


Because loops cannot be inside JSX directly.

â­ 5. Simple explanation
.map() = loop + return JSX correctly
for = loop only, cannot return JSX
ðŸ§  6. Super simple analogy

Think of .map() as:

ðŸ§º â€œTake each item â†’ transform it â†’ give me a new basket.â€

But for loop is:

ðŸ” â€œJust repeat this code; Iâ€™ll do the work myself.â€

ðŸŽ¯ Example showing the difference
With .map() (React-friendly)
const nums = [1, 2, 3];

const doubled = nums.map(n => n * 2);
// [2, 4, 6]

With loop
const nums = [1, 2, 3];
let doubled = [];

for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
  doubled.push(nums[i] * 2);
}
// [2, 4, 6]


âž¡ .map() does the whole thing in one line.

